post_text:
FSH Elementary 1st - 5th grade parents,

1st-5th grade students in the district are given Google accounts each year as part of their digital learning in school. In order for your child's teacher, as well as the technology department, to support you in remote learning, we have reset all Google passwords in these grade levels today. Please know that if your child has still been using their Google account from last year, that they will now be unable to sign in.

If you checked out a Chromebook, you will receive their new password with their device on Monday at distribution. If you did not check out a Chromebook, your child's teacher will reach out to you before school starts with their new login information. Thank you for your patience with this transition to the beginning of the school year in a remote learning environment.

post_text:
JUNIORS AND SENIORS!

Your new Chromebooks are coming sooner than expected. Barring any unforeseen events, we’ll have them ready for next Friday’s second round of distribution. So, we will NOT hand out Jr and Sr Chromebooks tomorrow or Saturday. You can get your brand new devices next week. If you’ve already filled out the form, no action is needed other than to show up next Friday.

If you absolutely, positively, unequivocally need a device right now, then you can come pick up a Chromebook but you’ll have to come back next Friday to swap it out.

Thanks!

post_text: Due to the recent spike in COVID-19 cases in Bexar County and in the interest of the health and safety of our FSHISD staff and community, all FSHISD campuses and offices will be closed until further notice. Key FSHISD personnel will work remotely from home and will be able to meet the needs of our community via phone and email. For staff extensions and email address, click the Meet Our Staff buttons on any of our campus pages or the Meet our Central Office Staff under Explore FSHISD on the district page.

post_text: We invite everyone to join us online as we celebrate the accomplishments of the 2020 Graduating Class of Robert G. Cole High School. The live stream will start at 2:45 pm on Friday, May 22. At 2:50, we will air a special video tribute to all our seniors. The commencement ceremony will start at 3:00 pm. You can watch the stream on this Facebook page, our Twitter page (www.twitter.com/fshisd), or our YouTube page (www.youtube.com/fshisd).

post_text:
FREE MEALS UPDATE

Fort Sam Houston ISD is continuing to provide free meals to all students and their younger siblings. For those families who normally pay for their meals, you may have noticed that your student’s meal account is being charged. These charges were made solely for reporting purposes and will be reversed from your child’s account. The available balance will be the amount prior to the school closing on March 16. We appreciate your patience as we work through this process.

The District will observe the April 10 and April 24 holidays on our calendar. On the Thursday preceding these holidays, additional meals will be provided to families for Friday.

Continue to check the District’s website and social media for COVID-19 updates and please be safe.
text:
FREE MEALS UPDATE

Fort Sam Houston ISD is continuing to provide free meals to all students and their younger siblings. For those families who normally pay for their meals, you may have noticed that your student’s meal account is being charged. These charges were made solely for reporting purposes and will be reversed from your child’s account. The available balance will be the amount prior to the school closing on March 16. We appreciate your patience as we work through this process.

The District will observe the April 10 and April 24 holidays on our calendar. On the Thursday preceding these holidays, additional meals will be provided to families for Friday.

Continue to check the District’s website and social media for COVID-19 updates and please be safe.

post_text:
Great idea from Cole Culinary Arts Teacher, Ms. Sarah Paqueno:

"During this 'Stay Home' time it's important to focus on the wellness of you and your family. There's no better way to do that than by cooking a delicious meal for you and your family to enjoy. Check that pantry and fridge and get creative with the ingredients on hand! Dust off those cookbooks, load up Netflix food shows, and YouTube food channels, and look for inspiration! I challenge you to get in the kitchen, get cooking, and together we can provide inspiration for one another!"

Share your amazing culinary creations with everyone here, on Twitter, or Instagram using #FSHISDCookAnywhere

post_text: The Cougar Boys Soccer team took 4th place at the Pleasanton tournament this past weekend. The boys defeated Beeville 3-1 with goals scored by Gonzalo Aliaga with 2 and Alec Wojak with 1. The boys lost a close game to Pleasanton 0-1 and then advanced to Saturday playing Floresville for 3rd. The game ended in a tie at 1-1 then went into a shoot out. Both teams scored 3 goals each and then went into sudden death where the boys fell short on the fist attempt. The boys were led in scoring by Gonzalo Aliaga with 2 goals, Matthew Knell and Pedro Gonzalez with 1 each. Brady Mitchell had a great tournament along with the defensive line for the Cougars. We have a quick turnaround and play Poteet at 5pm here at home. Please come out and support your boys.

post_text:
JV and VARSITY GIRLS

The Lady Cougars hosted the Ingram Lady Warriors on Friday night for their district opener. With outstanding team effort, JV went back and forth for a close game until the final buzzer. Hustle plays and big steals from Ashia Delanie and Nayeli Villegas late in the game helped seal the victory with a final score of 27 to 26.

The Varsity girls battled through the aggressive Lady Warriors. With another close game until the final minutes, the Varsity Lady Cougars were also able to get the win with a final score of 47 to 33. Leading scores for your Lady Cougars were Valerie Villegas, Nadja Babilonia-Lopez, and Avea Walters. The teams will be back in action this Tuesday in Comfort.

Cole Photography students and teachers competed in the Association of Texas Photography Instructors national photo contest this past weekend. With over 7000 entries from schools across the country and in Canada, 17 Cole students were recognized for their work in 9 different categories. Please congratulate the following photographers for their award winning work:

Chase Marafioto won 1st place in Beginning Advertising (winning image below), Hannah Cook won 2nd place in Advanced Advertising, and Payton Cunningham won 3rd place in Environmental Portrait. post_text:
Please congratulate both Boys' and Girls' Cross Country teams on an outstanding performance last Saturday at the UIL State Meet. Both teams displayed heart and a fierce determination to be recognized as some of the top runners in the State. All team members ran their personal best times, surpassing all expectations.

The boys team finished as the 4th best 3A team in the State, missing the podium by 26 points. The boys also impressively beat the Regional champions, Lytle HS this past weekend.

The girls finished in 9th place in the State and our very own Freshman, Finley Hunting was the State runner up, (finishing in 2nd place), out of a field of 150 runners, with a time of 11:36 and receiving the silver medal.

These student athletes have worked very hard all season long to become the BEST! They have represented this District, this Campus and this Cross Country program with pride, honor and class. Congratulations, Cole Cougar Cross Country.

post_text:
Congratulations to the Varsity Girls' and Boys' Cross Country teams on a very exciting day at the UIL Region IV Championships. Your Cole Cougars represented the region with grit and persistence and they both advanced to the UIL State meet on November 9th at Old Settlers Park in Round Rock Texas. The Boys' team was the Regional Runners up as they finally conquered their nemesis Luling HS. We will now set our eyes on Lytle at the State Meet. Freshman Anthony Meyer was a 4th place medalist overall out of 160 runners. David, Matt, James, Drew, Elijah and Parker were not far behind.

The girls also turned in another amazing race. Freshman Finley Hunting was the Regional Runner up, giving the champ all she could handle during the race. The girls team finished in 3rd place overall, along with Nadja, Audrey, Cami, and Rachel running the best race of the season. Maricah and Amy also improving with every race.

Way to Go Cougars!! On to State!!!!

Last night your 7th grade football team took on cross town rival Randolph at home and played a hard fought game. It was a close game throughout, but your Cole Cougars came up short 14-0. They have the next week off before traveling to Jourdanton for the last game of the season.

The JV Cougars have an off week next week then will host Jourdanton the following Thursday.

post_text:
The 8th grade Lady Cougars battled the Ingram Lady Warrriors in the last away game of their season. The B team went up early in their first set behind Gabby Cunningham's tough serves, but the home team was able to take the set. Angelina Escobar and Emma Bowman both helped pull the Lady Cougars from behind to tie the second set at 18-18. Unfortunately, the Ingram Lady Warriors took the win in the second set and game. The A team also battled and fought through an exciting three set game. Your Lady Cougars took the first set winning 26-24 with help from Shaneal Carter's front row defense and tips. The Lady Warriors answered back by taking the second set 25-23 which ultimately led to a tight third set. The focused and determined A team closed a gap in the third set with whole team hustle and heart but fell short with a score of 15-13.

Both teams will use this week to prepare to host Comfort in their last game of the season on Monday, October 28 starting at 5PM the Cole Gym.

This was definitely a game in which the talents of every girl on the team were evident. This was a big win for the girls and we are very proud.

post_text:
Please congratulate your middle school cross country team on a excellent finish at their district meet yesterday in Ingram.

Your 7th grade girls placed 3rd overall as a team with Serena Chavez as the standout runner finishing in 2nd place overall.

For the 7th grade boys, they dominated the field winning the district title with 5 runners finishing in the top 10 overall. Garrison Barker was the top runner finishing in 1st place with Preston Remly right behind him in 2nd. Johnathon Requenes finished in 4th, Israel Chavez was 6th and Greyson Moorman finished in 10th.

For the 8th girls, they also won the District Championship in impressive fashion as Madison Kiston finished in 1st with Dakota Gaston right behind in 2nd, and Isabella Perkins in 3rd to help lead their team to the title.

In the 8th grade boys division the team placed 2nd place overall with Rocky Vela as the top runner finishing in 3rd, James Livingston in 4th, and Elijah Pugh in 5th to help lead the team.

Last night your 7th grade Cole Cougars took on the Cotulla Cowboys. Throughout the entire game they fought hard and as short handed as they were they ran out of gas and came up short 32-6. The boys will work hard next week as we get ready to travel to Lytle next Thursday. Thanks for all your support!

Please congratulate your 8th grade cougar football team on their victory over Cotulla last night. After a slow start and a 6-0 lead at halftime, your cougars hit the reset button again to dominate in the second half. Your AICW player of the game is the cougar defense with two pick sixes and a shutout of 30-0. They look forward to next week in facing Lytle.

The JV Football team traveled to Cotulla Thursday night and fought valiantly throughout the whole evening but came up short 28-0 to the Cowboys. The team showed great effort and fight all evening but weren't able to manage a victory. The JV Cougars are 1-4-2 on the season and host Lytle next Thursday evening.

post_text: The Cole Swim and Dive Team had a very successful week. In competing in two swim and dive meets in 8 days, 4 school records were broken. The boys team finished 2nd in the opening meet of the year competing against 16 teams, the girls finished 10 out of 17. The combined team finished 4th place. With very impressive swims by sophomore Beaux Tobiason and Junior Alicia Elizalde. Diving had two records broken, Freshman Chase Marafioto for his 1st place performance in the 11 dive competition and Senior Ali Williams for her 2nd place in the 6 dive meet, both new school records. Last nights meet also included most swimmers recording fastest times with Junior Eion McGrath breaking the school records in 50 Breast stroke, and the 100 IM. Congratulations Cougar Swimmers.

post_text:
This weekend the 7th grade volleyball teams traveled to Bandera for the Bandera volleyball tournament. 7th grade B team showed up ready to work! Our girls were moving their feet and played aggressive at the net. Isabella Parker had 5 blocks and 2 kills in a single game! Overall the girls did outstanding in the tournament, displaying just how much growth they have undergone this season.

The A team started the day with amazing pool play, first beating Medina Valley in straight sets, then beating the hosting Bandera team in straight sets. The girls then played Alta Loma, losing the first set, but battling back to win the second, but losing a tough third set. The girls headed into bracket play in second, but came face to face with Loma, losing in straight sets. Though our team was down 4 players this weekend, the team played very well and received many compliments from officials regarding their play. I am very proud of how the girls continue to grow.

Tonight we take on the Randolph Ro-Hawks at home at 5pm.

post_text: Homecoming is a high school tradition stretching back decades. It’s weekly festivities, voting for the court, pep rallies, tailgating, and the dance, but the one thing that could ruin it all is the football team taking an loss. Well, your Cole Cougars did not disappoint. The boys put on a show, defeating the visiting Nixon-Smiley Mustangs by a score of 41-19. The Offense was spear headed by an outstanding performance from Jaizon Brooks, who finished the night with over 200 yards and 4 Touchdowns on 18 carries. The Cougar Defensive unit held strong behind a season high 20 tackles from Mathew Knell, who was followed closely by Chase Reilly tallying 17 of his own. With a successful Homecoming showing your Cougars set their sights on their first district opponent, the Karnes City Badgers who will travel to Cole this Friday. Please congratulate the varsity football team and wish them luck in their next contest.

The B team fell to the Lady Warriors in the first set, but rallied as a team in the second set to come away with a win ending their game in a tie. The A team went point for point throughout their game with strong serves from Angelena Gordish and hustle plays from several Lady Cougars. Unfortunately, we could not clinch the win. Both teams will prepare this week for their next game on the road in Comfort-Monday Sept, 23.

post_text:
Please congratulate the Cole Varsity football team for their 41-21 win over San Antonio Christian Friday night on the road. The offense was paced behind the work in the trenches of our offensive line Cruz Palacios, Jayson Clinton, Francisco Peguero, Austin Montanez, and Cyrus Vaughn. They paved the way for the running backs and did a great job protecting the QB for 3 touchdown passes and a great overall offensive performance.

The defense was paced by the play of Matthew Knell, Chase Rielly and Rechod Johnson and was able to pick up a score of their own before halftime to give us great momentum heading in to half.

Come out and support the team as we will play Nixon Smiley for homecoming this coming Friday.

post_text:
Dear FSHISD Parents,

At approximately 1245 on Friday, August 30, one of our district email accounts sent out a mass email in regards to an invoice that needed attention. If opened, the email asked the recipient for a username and password. This email was spam and was generated by an outside entity. We have taken steps internally to quarantine the email. If you received this email and followed the link, you are strongly encouraged to change your password to any account you may have entered. We apologize for the inconvenience and are taking additional steps to lessen the threat from happening again.

Thank you for your understanding. We hope you have a restful and enjoyable Labor Day Weekend.

If you received this email and followed the link, you are strongly encouraged to change your password to any account you may have entered. We apologize for the inconvenience and are taking additional steps to lessen the threat from happening again.

Thank you for your understanding. We hope you have a restful and enjoyable Labor Day Weekend.

VOLLEYBALL NEWS!
Our 8th grade Lady Cougar volleyball teams opened their season last night against the Marion Lady Bulldogs. B team started the night off, and while they fell short of grabbing the win-notable highlights include strong serves by Gabrielle Cunningham, consistent passing by Angelina Escboar, and all around team hustle from beginning to end. post_text:
Early Chromebook Pickup!

The new school year is right around the corner! Once again, we're giving 7th - 12th grade students the opportunity to get their Chromebooks early. This year’s pickup day is Thursday, August 15th. It is not required that you pick up your Chromebook early, but it will help both you and our teachers if you do! You must be enrolled for the 2019 - 2020 school year by the date of the pickup.

Early Chromebook distribution will be held on Thursday, August 15th in the High School Mall Area. Students may come during the following times:

7th & 8th Grade - 8:00 am - 10:00 am
9th & 10th Grade - 10:00 am - Noon
11th & 12th Grade - 1:00 pm - 3:00 pm
Any Grade - 3:00 - 4:30

*If you have siblings at Cole, all of you can come at the same time. Pick any of your designated times.

Students must come with a signed Student/Parent Chromebook Agreement Form to receive their Chromebook (available on our website). Do NOT give your signed form to anyone else except the staff working at the Chromebook pickup on August 15th.

If you have any questions, email Dr. Rios at rrios@fshisd.net.

post_text: The Fort Sam Houston Independent School District is soliciting for nominees to be considered for 2 openings on the Board of Trustees. The positions must be filled by either a military member or civilian living on or employed by Joint Base San Antonio-Fort Sam Houston. To qualify for the board, a volunteer must be 18 years of age or older, a U.S. citizen, and a qualified voter. Trustees will take an official oath of office and serve without compensation. Interested applicants must submit a resume no later than 5 p.m., June 28, 2019 to the School Liaison Officer at 2380 Stanley Road, Building 124, Room 102. For more information, call (210) 221-2214 or 221-2256
text: The Fort Sam Houston Independent School District is soliciting for nominees to be considered for 2 openings on the Board of Trustees. The positions must be filled by either a military member or civilian living on or employed by Joint Base San Antonio-Fort Sam Houston. To qualify for the board, a volunteer must be 18 years of age or older, a U.S. citizen, and a qualified voter. Trustees will take an official oath of office and serve without compensation. Interested applicants must submit a resume no later than 5 p.m., June 28, 2019 to the School Liaison Officer at 2380 Stanley Road, Building 124, Room 102. For more information, call (210) 221-2214 or 221-2256

post_text:
Six months ago, National Public Radio (NPR) challenged schools across the nation to get creative and produce podcasts for a national competition. Mrs. Garatoni took the challenge and her PreAP English II classes put on their broadcasting hats and got to work. On Tuesday, May 14th, NPR featured some of the high school podcast finalists in a piece on NPR’s evening news show, All Things Considered. Out of over 25,000 entries, Cole’s entry “Growing Up Military” was picked as a finalist and snippet of it was featured on the show. 10th graders Garrett Barnard, Joseph Huisken, and Julian Longoria created the podcast. It was very well received by NPR and is an accurate and thoughtful look at what it is like to be a military child. Way to go Cougars!

Here is a link to the NPR broadcast of “All Things
Considered”. The “Growing Up Military” snippet happens around the 1:32 mark. https://www.wyso.org/post/students-around-us-open-about-their-lives-npr-podcast-challenge

Here is a link to the entire podcast.https://drive.google.com/file/d/1SfbwnxbpvKyBhAj20e_uqN5p-E9lZQgO/view?usp=sharing

post_text:
ELEMENTARY STUDENT'S STORY GOES NATIONAL!

In early 2018, current FSH Elementary student Samantha White submitted a story to a popular national podcast, Story Pirates. Her story, “Dreaming Sheep”, was selected to be turned into a song and in February of 2018, Samantha’s Dreaming Sheep song aired on the Story Pirates podcast. That, in itself, is quite a feat!

Fast forward to today, and Samantha and her family just learned that Dreaming Sheep will be one of only a handful of songs featured on Story Pirates' second CD! The album will be released nationally on May 31st.

When asked what inspired her to write and submit her story Samantha said, “When I listened to other kid's stories, it inspired me to write my story. I wanted to write about my stuffed animal sheep, Ba-Ba, doing the same things that I did every day." We are sure glad she did!

Congratulations, Samantha. We’re very proud of you!

Go Public Story Pirates

Listen to the original podcast here:
https://cms.megaphone.fm/channel/storypirates?selected=GLT4394272362

This spring, Cole's English 2 Pre-AP students participated in the NPR Student Podcast Challenge. Out of over 6000 entries, two of our podcasts were recognized.

The podcast “Growing Up Military" - created by Joseph Huisken, Garrett Barnard, and Julian Longoria - was named a finalist in the high school category and considered "one of the absolute top submissions." Congratulations to Joseph, Garrett and Julian! You can listen to their podcast entry here: http://bit.ly/2V8UT6g

Congratulations, too, to Madison Curtis, Camilia Castillo Rodriguez, and Miguel Manzueta for their podcast "What is Love" which received an honorable mention - the judges recognized them as "standouts." Youn can hear theirs here: http://bit.ly/2vpbKCk

NPR will be sending these groups a certificate to recognize their outstanding work. Way to go, Cougars!

PCS Season got you down? Join us Friday, May 3rd @ 10:45 am for a "Smooth Transitions" seminar. Moves are stressful, especially when children are involved. We’ll discuss ways to make your child’s transition to a new school as smooth as possible. Meet other parents, share your own experiences and leave prepared to take on the WORLD! (or at least your next move…) You’ll also receive FREE Sesame Street moving goodies for your child.

post_text: Please congratulate the Cole Robotics Teams for competing at the state level of the 2019 TCEA Robotics Challenge! Over 1,200 teams competed at the area level to get to state and 3 Cole teams ranked in the top 10%, approximately 120 teams, that went on to state this past Saturday, 4/27. All 3 Cole teams improved their scores and ranked in the top 5% overall across the state at the end of the contest. The 8th graders on the Cole State Teams were: Anthony Meyer, Ethan Soliz, Alex Martinez-Cepeda, Elliana Bay, Isabel Suarez, Jonas Amis, Mark Mangio, and Chandler Bahnemann. Way to go Cougars!

post_text:
The Lady Cougars varsity softball team battled against the Blanco Lady Panthers in their bi-district playoff game. Autumn Creason came through home plate off a hit from Sophia Alaniz to put us on the board. Defensively, outfielders Elena Barrera, Izzy Villanueva, and Veronica Rios all contributed with catches off big hitters. While the Lady Cougars’ were not able to extend their season to the next round-they have completed a successful season and represented Cole the Cougar Way.

Thank you for all the support through our long season, and to everyone that made the trip out to Marion. All is appreciated!

post_text: The JV and Varsity softball teams went on the road for their last district game against the Ingram Lady Warriors. Both teams came home to ring the victory bell! For the JV squad, Gloria Oueda went two for two at bats. The entire team tore up the base path with six girls stealing at least two bases. The Varsity team continued with high momentum. The Lady Cougars started game up 5-0, and pulled away with 9 runs in the second inning. Freshmen Izzy Villanueva went 3 of 4 with bunts, and a double play connection between Erika Nova, Autumn Creason and Kara Mercer sealed the win.

post_text: The Cole varsity softball team hosted the Comfort Deer for their last home game of the regular season. Our Lady Cougars battled from inning to inning behind pitcher, Sophia Alaniz. Sophomore, Grace Miskovsky had 2 RBIs to bring in Monica Echevarria, and while we picked up momentum bottom of the 4th inning, the Comfort Deer ultimately took the W. The varsity squad looks to lock in and prepare for a pivotal game in district play this Friday on the road against Randolph starting at 4PM. If you are looking for some excitement Friday afternoon, the Randolph softball field is the place to be!

Congratulations to senior Rose McConnell who has been awarded a one-time scholarship of $750 to the university or college of her choice by the Alamo Area Association for Curriculum and Development. The scholarship is for students aspiring to become educators. Way to go, Rose!
(Rose is pictured here with FSH Elementary Principal and AAASCD Scholarship Chair, Dr. Joseph Cerna.)
